question=Check the code and the review. Are the findings in the review and the suggested solution correct?

<code>
Original code for a Spring Cloud Gateway application:
```java
import org.springframework.cloud.gateway.filter.*;
import org.springframework.data.redis.core.*;

class ConcurrentUserLimiter implements GatewayFilter {
    public Mono<Void> filter(ServerWebExchange exchange, GatewayFilterChain chain) {
        String userId = getUserId();

        ReactiveSetOperations<String, String> setOps = redisTemplate.opsForSet();

        // add the user ID to the set
        return setOps.add(SET_KEY, userId)
            .flatMap(added -> {
                // set TTL only if this is the very first member being added to the set, i.e. the set was just created by this SADD operation
                if (added == 1L) {
                    // check if TTL marker exists; if not, set TTL and mark flag
                    return redisTemplate.hasKey(TTL_KEY)
                        .flatMap(ttlMarkerExists -> {
                            if (ttlMarkerExists) {
                                // TTL already set in a previous request, don't reset it
                                logger.debug("TTL already set for {}", SET_KEY);
                                return Mono.just(added);
                            }
                            // first time: set TTL, mark initialised
                            logger.debug("Initialising TTL");
                            return redisTemplate.expire(SET_KEY, ttl)
                                .then(redisTemplate.opsForValue().set(TTL_KEY, "initialised", ttl))
                                .thenReturn(added);
                        });
                }
                // duplicate user ID, don't touch TTL
                return Mono.just(added);
            })
            .then(setOps.size(SET_KEY))
            .flatMap(size -> {
                if (size > MAX_USERS) {
                    logger.warn("Too many users");
                    ServerHttpResponse response = exchange.getResponse();
                    response.setStatusCode(HttpStatus.TOO_MANY_REQUESTS);
                    return response.setComplete();
                }
                return chain.filter(exchange);
            });
    }
}
```
</code>

Received review:
<review>
### Overview
This code is a Spring Cloud Gateway filter designed to limit the number of concurrent unique users accessing the application. It uses a Redis Set to store unique user IDs and rejects requests with a 429 Too Many Requests status if the number of users in the Set exceeds a predefined MAX_USERS limit. It also attempts to assign a Time-To-Live (TTL) to the Set to reset the user limit periodically.

### Bugs and Issues
There are several bugs in this implementation, including a critical functional flaw, logical errors, and race conditions.

#### 1. Critical Bug: System Lockout upon Limit Breach
The user ID is added to the Redis Set (setOps.add) before the total size of the Set is checked.
- The Problem: If the Set is currently at maximum capacity (size == MAX_USERS), a new user's ID is still added. The Set size becomes MAX_USERS + 1, and the request is rejected.
- The Consequence: Because the size is now strictly greater than MAX_USERS, every subsequent request will be rejected. This includes requests from the originally authorized users who were correctly added before the limit was reached. The gateway locks up for everyone until the TTL expires and clears the Set.

#### 2. Logical Bug: Misinterpretation of SADD Return Value
The code comment states: // set TTL only if this is the very first member being added... i.e. the set was just created.
- The Problem: In Redis, the SADD command (which backs setOps.add) returns 1 when the specific element provided was not already in the Set, and 0 if it was. It does not indicate whether the Set itself was just created.
- The Consequence: The if (added == 1L) block and its inner hasKey(TTL_KEY) check will execute for every new user added to the Set, rather than just the first one. This generates unnecessary network round-trips to Redis.

#### 3. Race Conditions and Non-Atomicity
The filter performs multiple sequential, non-atomic Redis operations (SADD, hasKey, expire, SET, SCARD). In a highly concurrent environment like an API Gateway, this causes unpredictable states:
- Missing TTL (Memory Leak): If the application crashes or a network error occurs immediately after SADD but before expire() is executed, the Redis Set will be left without an expiration, creating a memory leak.
- Inconsistent Rejections: If two new user requests arrive concurrently when the Set is at MAX_USERS - 1, both might execute SADD before either checks the size. Both will increment the Set size, both will see a size of MAX_USERS + 1, and both will be rejected, even though one should have been admitted.

#### 4. Unnecessary Complexity (TTL_KEY)
The code introduces a secondary key (TTL_KEY) to track whether a TTL has been applied to the main Set.
- The Problem: Using a separate tracking key is an anti-pattern. You can check the TTL of the original Set directly using the Redis TTL or PTTL commands (e.g., redisTemplate.getExpire(SET_KEY)). Managing two distinct keys increases the risk of the data state becoming desynchronized.

### Recommended Solution
To fix all race conditions and logic errors, and to reduce network round-trips from five to one, the logic should be rewritten into a single atomic Redis Lua script.

1. Lua Script (limiter.lua) - checks size and membership before adding a new user:
    local set_key = KEYS[1]
    local user_id = ARGV[1]
    local max_users = tonumber(ARGV[2])
    local ttl_seconds = tonumber(ARGV[3])
    local is_member = redis.call('SISMEMBER', set_key, user_id)
    if is_member == 1 then return 1 end
    local current_size = redis.call('SCARD', set_key)
    if current_size >= max_users then return 0 end
    redis.call('SADD', set_key, user_id)
    if current_size == 0 then redis.call('EXPIRE', set_key, ttl_seconds) end
    return 1

2. Java Integration - execute the script via reactive Redis template, reject when result == 0L.
